{"questionId":"9481","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>This question asks you to investigate some properties of the sequence of functions of the&nbsp;form <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{f_n}(x) = {\\text{cos}}\\left( {n\\,{\\text{arccos}}\\,x} \\right)\">\n  <mrow>\n    <msub>\n      <mi>f</mi>\n      <mi>n</mi>\n    </msub>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo>\n  <mi>x</mi>\n  <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>cos</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mrow>\n      <mi>n</mi>\n      <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n      <mrow>\n        <mtext>arccos</mtext>\n      </mrow>\n      <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n    </mrow>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>, −1 ≤ <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x\">\n  <mi>x</mi>\n</math></span> ≤ 1 and <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"n \\in {\\mathbb{Z}^ + }\">\n  <mi>n</mi>\n  <mo>∈</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <msup>\n      <mrow>\n        <mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi>\n      </mrow>\n      <mo>+</mo>\n    </msup>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>.</p>\n<p><strong>Important:</strong> When sketching graphs in this question, you are <strong>not</strong> required to find the&nbsp;coordinates of any axes intercepts or the coordinates of any stationary points unless requested.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>For odd values of <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"n\">\n  <mi>n</mi>\n</math></span> &gt; 2, use your graphic display calculator to systematically vary the&nbsp;value of <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"n\">\n  <mi>n</mi>\n</math></span>. Hence suggest an expression for odd values of <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"n\">\n  <mi>n</mi>\n</math></span> describing, in terms of <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"n\">\n  <mi>n</mi>\n</math></span>,&nbsp;the number of</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>local minimum points;</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{{n - 1}}{2}\"> <mfrac> <mrow> <mi>n</mi> <mo>−</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mn>2</mn> </mfrac> </math></span>&nbsp;local minimum points &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Allow follow through from an incorrect local maximum formula expression.</p>\n<p><em><strong>[1 mark]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"9481","referenceCode":"SPM.3.AHL.TZ0.2b.ii","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"local minimum points;","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"b.ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 5 —Calculus","Topic 5 —Calculus","SL 5.6—Differentiating polynomials n E Q. Chain, product and quotient rules","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.9—Reciprocal trig ratios and their pythagorean identities. Inverse circular functions"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}